  "nextSessionNotes": "Session 42: Tarjei Vesaas — the greatest Nynorsk prose writer, from the same Vinje as A.O. Vinje, second cousin of Eivind Groven. Nominated for the Nobel Prize 57 times, never won. Wrote 'Fuglane' (The Birds) — Karl Ove Knausgård's 'best Norwegian novel ever' — about Mattis, a simple-minded man who sees a woodcock change its flight and experiences wonder nobody else shares. Wrote 'Is-slottet' (The Ice Palace) — a girl enters a frozen waterfall and doesn't come out. Married poet Halldis Moren Vesaas, who translated Dickinson and Shakespeare into Nynorsk and served Det Norske Teatret for 55 years. Hid his occupation novel in a zinc box. His poem 'Lake Angst' names the landscape as psychology. His poem appeared in SKAM, reaching twenty-first century teenagers. Engagement 0.95. The Nynorsk lineage is now fully traced: Aasen → Vinje → Vesaas → Groven → Hauge. Next could follow: Jan Garbarek's settings of Hauge's poems (closing the music-language circle), Robert Bly's translations (the Atlantic bridge), Halldis's own poetry, or something entirely new — the Nynorsk arc feels complete. Could drift to weather, architecture, or back to music. The woodcock is hidden under a stone."
